If the prototype of MHD_itc_activate_ declares the second parameter as a non-const pointer (e.g. int MHD_itc_activate_(..., char *msg)), then this call passes a string literal "e" which is effectively const and the parameter should be const-qualified. That would violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13. To fix, declare the parameter as const char * (or otherwise ensure the function cannot/does not modify the pointed data).
</scenario>

